Data Modeling and Schema Design

Overview

The dataset follows a relational structure where the orders table acts as the central fact table. Supporting tables provide additional information about customers, products, sellers, and reviews.

This structure allows the analysis of order fulfillment performance, customer behavior, seller performance, and delivery efficiency.

⸻

Fact Table

orders

The orders table is the main transactional table in the dataset. Each row represents a single order placed on the marketplace.

Key columns

order_id
customer_id
order_status
order_purchase_timestamp
order_approved_at
order_delivered_carrier_date
order_delivered_customer_date

This table records the lifecycle of an order from purchase to delivery.

⸻

Bridge Table

order_items

The order_items table connects orders with products and sellers. A single order may contain multiple products, so this table allows one-to-many relationships between orders and products.

Key columns

order_id
product_id
seller_id
price
freight_value

This table enables analysis of seller performance and product category delivery performance.

⸻

Dimension Tables

customers

The customers table contains information about the buyers on the marketplace, including geographic location.

Key columns

customer_id
customer_city
customer_state

This table allows regional analysis of delivery performance.

⸻

products

The products table contains product catalog information.

Key columns

product_id
product_category_name

This table allows analysis of delivery performance by product category.

⸻

sellers

The sellers table contains information about marketplace sellers.

Key columns

seller_id
seller_city
seller_state

This table enables analysis of seller fulfillment performance.

⸻

order_reviews

The order_reviews table contains customer feedback and review scores.

Key columns

review_id
order_id
review_score

This table enables analysis of how delivery performance affects customer satisfaction.

⸻

Schema Relationships

The dataset follows a star-like relational structure centered around the orders table.

orders → order_items → products
orders → order_items → sellers
orders → customers
orders → order_reviews

This schema allows combining operational data, seller data, product data, and customer feedback to analyze the full order lifecycle.

⸻

Why This Data Model Works

This data model allows analysts to study the full order lifecycle by connecting operational events with customer, seller, and product attributes. Using this relational structure makes it possible to analyze delivery performance, seller efficiency, regional logistics differences, and customer satisfaction.
